# _redirects file conventions

## Rule order matters

Cloudflare Pages evaluates `_redirects` top-to-bottom and stops at the first match. **Specific path rules MUST come BEFORE splat rules.**

Wrangler flags performance warnings if a specific path (`/plumbing_002`, `/method`) sits below a splat (`/dash/*`, `/blog/*`) - meaning the specific rule never fires because the splat caught it first.

Reorder rules so specific paths come first:

```
# Specific exact paths
/some-specific-path /destination 301
/another-exact-path https://external.com/ 301

# Then splats
/some-path/* /catch-all-dest 301
```

## Comment every new rule with date + reason

```
# 2026-05-13: deck content + studio retired during portfolio rebrand. Old URLs redirect to root.
/blog / 301
/blog/* / 301
```

When the rule's reason isn't obvious 6 months later, the comment is what tells future-you (or future-Claude) whether the rule still applies.

## Wildcards vs splat captures

- `/path/*` matches any path under `/path/` (greedy).
- Use `:splat` in the destination ONLY if you need to forward the captured part. Most redirects we use go to fixed destinations (`/` or another exact URL), so `:splat` is rarely needed.

## Status codes

- `301` for permanent redirects (preferred for retired content).
- `302` for temporary redirects.
- `200` for rewrites (serves the destination's content while keeping the original URL in the browser bar) - currently used only for the `/dash/*` SPA pattern.
- `410` for explicitly Gone content (rare; SEO-aggressive signal to drop from indexes).
